1
00:00:00,841 --> 00:00:28,553
namo tassa bhagavato arahato sambha sambuddhasa namo tassa bhagavato arahato sambha sambuddhasa namo tassa bhagavato arahato sambha sambuddhasa

2
00:00:28,954 --> 00:00:32,999
Homage to the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:41,506 --> 00:00:56,200
So you can see how that exercise we've just done, loving kindness, metta, it's normally put under this word metta, but goodwill, developing goodwill, I prefer that to loving kindness.

4
00:00:56,659 --> 00:00:58,421
It sounds a bit mawkish to me.

5
00:01:00,881 --> 00:01:03,625
And you can see how it complements the vipassana, I hope.

6
00:01:06,808 --> 00:01:12,352
So, there's one side of our practice which is to do with purifying, the purgatory.

7
00:01:14,295 --> 00:01:20,301
And that includes also this insight, these insights into how we're creating suffering for ourselves.

8
00:01:21,162 --> 00:01:22,263
And that goes deep, remember.

9
00:01:23,024 --> 00:01:27,548
And on the other side, there's developing the heart, developing the heart of goodwill.

10
00:01:30,143 --> 00:01:37,451
And these are expressed as the illimitables, the four illimitables, love, compassion, joy, peace.

11
00:01:39,093 --> 00:01:43,680
And they're illimitable in what you might say is a horizontal and a vertical sense.

12
00:01:44,980 --> 00:01:47,864
Horizontally, they're meant to be innumerable beings.

13
00:01:48,566 --> 00:01:52,549
So there's no limit to the amount of beings that you can offer your goodwill to.

14
00:01:53,951 --> 00:01:54,453
Illimitable.

15
00:01:56,114 --> 00:01:57,096
We don't say infinite.

16
00:01:59,218 --> 00:02:06,731
And vertically, there's no end to the depth that you can develop that attitude.

17
00:02:09,175 --> 00:02:09,856
It's indefinite.

18
00:02:09,877 --> 00:02:15,225
You can keep on developing love until you become this enormous film star charismatic.

19
00:02:16,829 --> 00:02:19,252
People hang on to your every word and want to be hugged.

20
00:02:21,307 --> 00:02:31,058
And it's the same force that you'll see this afternoon that can be used to heal because it's also a very strong relationship to the body.

21
00:02:31,938 --> 00:02:39,366
Just remember that the mental force and the physical force, mental and physical energy in Buddhism is just a continuum.

22
00:02:39,608 --> 00:02:41,550
It's not as though they're completely separate.

23
00:02:41,569 --> 00:02:44,733
The one saturates the other.

24
00:02:44,973 --> 00:02:47,316
The mind saturates the body.

25
00:02:51,329 --> 00:03:00,978
And when it comes to the first one, love, the commentaries always talk about a near and a far enemy.

26
00:03:02,079 --> 00:03:04,141
An obvious one and a subtle one, that's what it means.

27
00:03:04,942 --> 00:03:08,705
So the obvious enemy of love is hate.

28
00:03:09,205 --> 00:03:10,247
That's pretty straightforward.

29
00:03:10,788 --> 00:03:12,370
You can't hate and love at the same time.

30
00:03:13,310 --> 00:03:14,512
Not exactly at the same time.

31
00:03:14,592 --> 00:03:16,753
You can hate somebody and love them in a sequence.

32
00:03:17,775 --> 00:03:20,037
You can't do it exactly at the same time.

33
00:03:21,669 --> 00:03:24,854
And hate of course closes the heart, it shuts it off.

34
00:03:27,538 --> 00:03:30,022
And remember, hatred and fear are flip sides.

35
00:03:35,991 --> 00:03:47,289
So it's said, I don't know how true this is, but the paranoid is afraid because they project their hatred into the other person's eyes.

36
00:03:51,504 --> 00:03:52,768
That's what we do often, isn't it?

37
00:03:54,091 --> 00:03:57,758
You might see a friend walking down the other side of the road and they don't acknowledge you.

38
00:03:57,939 --> 00:04:01,167
So you go away thinking I've said something wrong or they hate me now.

39
00:04:02,088 --> 00:04:03,372
But actually they just didn't notice you.

40
00:04:07,384 --> 00:04:11,549
So we undermine that hate by again allowing it to arise.

41
00:04:11,628 --> 00:04:13,950
Remember you can't kill a conditioning.

42
00:04:14,390 --> 00:04:16,793
You've really got to really accept that.

43
00:04:16,853 --> 00:04:21,418
You can't kill, you can't annihilate a conditioning.

44
00:04:21,937 --> 00:04:32,247
If there's hatred in the heart there's only one way it's going to be cured and that is to allow it to express itself and you have to be very careful not to fall into the fantasies.

45
00:04:34,389 --> 00:04:36,632
Even when we do it unwittingly

46
00:04:36,697 --> 00:04:39,581
There's a little development there.

47
00:04:40,283 --> 00:04:46,475
You've all had the experience of being slightly annoyed with somebody in the morning.

48
00:04:46,696 --> 00:04:49,480
They've said something at work or something.

49
00:04:49,500 --> 00:04:55,071
And quite unmindfully you've allowed this to sort of generate a little story.

50
00:04:56,072 --> 00:04:59,699
And it gets worse and worse and by the evening you've sort of strangled them and

51
00:05:02,127 --> 00:05:04,935
written poison letters and all that sort of stuff.

52
00:05:04,954 --> 00:05:05,918
And that's what the mind does.

53
00:05:05,958 --> 00:05:07,723
It'll generate, it'll proliferate.

54
00:05:09,387 --> 00:05:17,470
So stopping that, recognizing that, and just staying with the pain, staying with the hurt, you see, you're allowing it to die out.

55
00:05:18,613 --> 00:05:22,740
So that's what you've got to really grasp if we want to come to the end of hatred.

56
00:05:23,600 --> 00:05:32,074
And remember that all these negative things are not, how can we say, they're not dependent on an object.

57
00:05:32,173 --> 00:05:34,617
A disposition is not dependent on an object.

58
00:05:35,019 --> 00:05:41,988
The object is the button which when pressed allows this disposition to manifest.

59
00:05:44,264 --> 00:05:48,410
So the Buddha talks about two things, he talks about anusaya and kilesa.

60
00:05:48,750 --> 00:05:54,076
Anusaya is latent tendencies, latent tendencies.

61
00:05:54,096 --> 00:05:57,822
The fact is we don't know how much hatred we've got in the system.

62
00:05:58,523 --> 00:06:00,144
We don't know how much fear there is.

63
00:06:01,887 --> 00:06:05,632
That's just a fact, it's buried within the psyche somewhere, it's buried in the body.

64
00:06:06,334 --> 00:06:11,841
And suddenly when something happens, this hatred comes out, this fear comes out.

65
00:06:13,963 --> 00:06:18,031
And often it's entirely inappropriate to the situation, isn't it?

66
00:06:19,432 --> 00:06:20,675
You know, road rage, for instance.

67
00:06:20,714 --> 00:06:23,459
It might be that just on this occasion somebody cut you up.

68
00:06:24,961 --> 00:06:26,884
And suddenly you're full of this rage.

69
00:06:28,968 --> 00:06:34,437
You see, if they'd have done it and your business was good and you had a happy relationship, you'd just swear at a bit.

70
00:06:36,036 --> 00:06:41,262
But because you're in a bad mood, this rage comes out and you go out and stab them.

71
00:06:41,283 --> 00:06:41,944
It happens, doesn't it?

72
00:06:41,963 --> 00:06:42,425
It's terrible.

73
00:06:43,505 --> 00:06:44,307
Computer rage.

74
00:06:44,728 --> 00:06:49,112
How many of you have smashed up your computer?

75
00:06:49,132 --> 00:06:50,694
Totally inappropriate response.

76
00:06:53,418 --> 00:07:01,447
And sometimes we can get this inappropriate response, especially with objects or people whom, of course, we feel can't come back at us.

77
00:07:03,269 --> 00:07:03,569
You know?

78
00:07:03,951 --> 00:07:04,572
The child.

79
00:07:05,192 --> 00:07:05,593
The dog.

80
00:07:05,612 --> 00:07:05,773
The dog.

81
00:07:07,036 --> 00:07:12,303
They can't bite you back, so there's a sort of permission to let go of it.

82
00:07:14,367 --> 00:07:21,439
So what we have is this disposition and I liken it to a balloon and it's being held there, you see, with just this membrane being held there.

83
00:07:22,480 --> 00:07:28,149
Something happens and it's just that little pinprick and all of it tries to get out through that little hole.

84
00:07:29,345 --> 00:07:37,454
So this disposition, all the anger we have and the anxiety and all that, it's all there as a programming.

85
00:07:37,836 --> 00:07:39,137
It's a good way to really see it.

86
00:07:39,437 --> 00:07:41,379
It's just there as a latent programming.

87
00:07:42,120 --> 00:07:46,466
And you don't know how big it is until something allows it to manifest.

88
00:07:46,507 --> 00:07:51,213
And then it becomes this obvious thing, and that's what the Buddha refers to as a kilesa.

89
00:07:55,918 --> 00:07:57,461
I can't remember how they translate that now.

90
00:07:57,540 --> 00:07:57,822
Can you?

91
00:07:58,442 --> 00:07:58,963
Kilesa?

92
00:08:01,237 --> 00:08:08,286
Neurosis, that'll do.

93
00:08:08,307 --> 00:08:14,875
So that's part of our practice is to know what to do when something negative arises.

94
00:08:15,276 --> 00:08:16,516
That's part of our practice.

95
00:08:17,257 --> 00:08:23,466
And the real insight in this is to know that you can't do anything about this stuff

96
00:08:23,766 --> 00:08:25,911
except to allow it to burn out.

97
00:08:27,213 --> 00:08:27,653
And that's it.

98
00:08:27,853 --> 00:08:35,986
So in the scriptures the Buddha always talks about going from hatred to non-hatred, cruelty to non-cruelty, see this neutral state.

99
00:08:36,427 --> 00:08:38,030
Then there's the transformation.

100
00:08:38,951 --> 00:08:40,354
It's all the same energy, remember?

101
00:08:40,955 --> 00:08:50,331
So that which we hated, through the practice, through a generous practice, through these sorts of meditations like metta, become transformed.

102
00:08:51,424 --> 00:08:55,451
So the amount of hate we had eventually turns out to be the amount of love we have.

103
00:08:56,672 --> 00:08:58,235
And then of course we can develop love.

104
00:09:00,457 --> 00:09:03,142
So nothing is wasted in the universe.

105
00:09:03,241 --> 00:09:05,404
Nothing is wasted in the heart anyway.

106
00:09:07,067 --> 00:09:10,451
Everything eventually through this sort of practice becomes transformed.

107
00:09:11,092 --> 00:09:14,697
And you end up with the Buddha heart, the Buddha mind.

108
00:09:17,648 --> 00:09:21,753
Now the subtle enemy of love, of course, is attachment.

109
00:09:22,433 --> 00:09:24,417
And that's a difficult one.

110
00:09:24,437 --> 00:09:26,038
Because we have all sorts of attachments.

111
00:09:27,721 --> 00:09:36,812
Romantic attachments, erotic attachments, attachments to parents, attachments to their children, attachments to friends, attachments to cars.

112
00:09:36,952 --> 00:09:39,476
God, there's all sorts of attachments.

113
00:09:39,496 --> 00:09:45,565
And that attachment turns the person whom you love into an object.

114
00:09:46,686 --> 00:09:47,486
That's what you're doing.

115
00:09:49,254 --> 00:09:57,404
Because what an attachment does is it is seeking from that person that which I need to be happy.

116
00:09:59,366 --> 00:10:00,508
That's what an attachment does.

117
00:10:00,869 --> 00:10:07,657
So when we have an attachment to something, I only want from that person what makes me happy.

118
00:10:08,618 --> 00:10:18,570
As soon as they do something which doesn't come into that little circle of what I like and want, then I get that rejection, I get the hatred, I get the pushing away.

119
00:10:19,663 --> 00:10:21,427
So that isn't love.

120
00:10:22,308 --> 00:10:23,932
Now, you have to be very careful here.

121
00:10:24,133 --> 00:10:27,099
Not to think that therefore this is somehow immoral.

122
00:10:28,240 --> 00:10:31,466
You can't say that a parent's attachment to their child is immoral.

123
00:10:32,710 --> 00:10:33,530
But it's not skillful.

124
00:10:33,851 --> 00:10:34,133
That's all.

125
00:10:34,352 --> 00:10:35,394
It's just not skillful.

126
00:10:37,905 --> 00:10:40,671
So we see it in things like when a child gets hurt, you see.

127
00:10:40,831 --> 00:10:50,048
If a child is hurt and the parent sees that it's just a scratch or something, then of course they have this, you know, comfort, hugging, all that sort of stuff, it'll be alright, etc., etc.

128
00:10:51,831 --> 00:10:56,779
But if the parent sees that the child is really hurt, then there comes this enormous fear.

129
00:10:59,965 --> 00:11:01,567
And that doesn't help the situation, does it?

130
00:11:06,187 --> 00:11:08,409
So that's a real subtle one, that.

131
00:11:08,429 --> 00:11:10,572
You have to sort of really work with it.

132
00:11:11,212 --> 00:11:14,076
And again, you can't kill the attachment.

133
00:11:14,636 --> 00:11:15,957
You can't get rid of it.

134
00:11:16,337 --> 00:11:21,222
You can't sort of pretend it isn't there and develop this open-heartedness.

135
00:11:21,683 --> 00:11:23,345
It's just the gentle working with it.

136
00:11:23,905 --> 00:11:30,913
Now, in the discourse on that loving-kindness that I chant, the Buddha likens love to a mother.

137
00:11:31,905 --> 00:11:35,270
And he says that, are these four illimitables to a mother?

138
00:11:35,851 --> 00:11:40,317
So, with the youngest child, I think it's in this sequence, can't be exact.

139
00:11:40,958 --> 00:11:42,662
With the youngest child, she's a friend.

140
00:11:43,863 --> 00:11:44,965
A friendly relationship.

141
00:11:46,106 --> 00:11:49,091
With the child who's sick, she's compassionate, looks after the child.

142
00:11:50,131 --> 00:11:53,998
With the child who's successful, she's full of sympathetic joy.

143
00:11:54,873 --> 00:11:57,956
And with the child that leaves home, she's equanimous.

144
00:11:59,479 --> 00:12:00,941
Being able to let somebody go.

145
00:12:01,442 --> 00:12:03,705
So that's the sign of a detached love.

146
00:12:04,586 --> 00:12:08,850
Because what you're saying to the person is, you're utterly free to be as you are.

147
00:12:10,232 --> 00:12:11,615
You're utterly free to be as you are.

148
00:12:11,894 --> 00:12:13,076
I don't need you.

149
00:12:14,177 --> 00:12:18,303
So we think that part of our love contract is need.

150
00:12:18,563 --> 00:12:19,985
But that need is neurotic.

151
00:12:22,817 --> 00:12:26,384
That need is coming because we're not looking into ourselves for the fullness.

152
00:12:27,886 --> 00:12:32,235
So that's why the Buddha says, you know, the spiritual person, seek solitude.

153
00:12:33,616 --> 00:12:35,120
Be as lonely as a rhinoceros.

154
00:12:36,822 --> 00:12:46,259
I don't know anything about rhinoceros, but whatever the habits of a rhinoceros are, they're definitely to be alone.

155
00:12:48,264 --> 00:12:52,956
And that distinction between being alone, being solitudinous, and loneliness.

156
00:12:53,238 --> 00:12:54,299
See, you know the difference, eh?

157
00:12:54,861 --> 00:12:57,368
See, when you're lonely, there's that hole.

158
00:12:58,090 --> 00:12:59,253
You want somebody to fill it.

159
00:12:59,573 --> 00:13:01,258
So you go and get this person and fill it.

160
00:13:01,298 --> 00:13:02,260
There's your attachment.

161
00:13:02,500 --> 00:13:05,227
You call it love.

162
00:13:05,714 --> 00:13:09,620
But actually, when that loneliness comes, we should seek that solitude.

163
00:13:09,659 --> 00:13:10,942
We should stay by ourselves.

164
00:13:11,462 --> 00:13:16,631
And instead of calling up that friend, turning on the TV, making a cup of tea, we should do the vipassana.

165
00:13:17,393 --> 00:13:19,316
We should stay with that sense of loneliness.

166
00:13:21,239 --> 00:13:26,668
As that begins to dissipate, what comes in its stead?

167
00:13:27,288 --> 00:13:30,894
We have love to hatred, cruelty to compassion.

168
00:13:31,802 --> 00:13:32,744
Loneliness to what?

169
00:13:33,465 --> 00:13:34,125
To solitude.

170
00:13:34,907 --> 00:13:37,590
Solitude is being at peace, at one with oneself.

171
00:13:39,312 --> 00:13:40,273
Occasionally you feel it.

172
00:13:42,274 --> 00:13:43,756
But these things have to be developed.

173
00:13:44,879 --> 00:13:49,604
And you have to not be confused by those things that are negative in us.

174
00:13:52,868 --> 00:13:55,431
They'll always give you a good excuse, you know.

175
00:13:56,474 --> 00:13:58,817
You might not, for instance, recognize the loneliness.

176
00:13:59,158 --> 00:14:02,461
You say to yourself, ah, Mary, yeah, I'll give her a ring.

177
00:14:02,481 --> 00:14:06,969
I'm sure she'd like to hear from me.

178
00:14:06,989 --> 00:14:09,331
You displace it onto this poor person.

179
00:14:10,212 --> 00:14:17,823
And in fact, you haven't recognized, you haven't locked into your own sense of loneliness.

180
00:14:18,783 --> 00:14:31,802
So all you can do is, and this is the whole point of vipassana, is to lift that awareness, that intelligence, so that during the day one is with the mind, one is with the heart, one doesn't get caught up in it.

181
00:14:32,322 --> 00:14:35,047
That's the whole point of developing the vipassana mind.

182
00:14:35,086 --> 00:14:37,710
During the day you see, ah, lonely, you see.

183
00:14:37,750 --> 00:14:40,955
Then you see that desire to seek this, seek that.

184
00:14:41,355 --> 00:14:43,018
You just stay still, wait for it to pass.

185
00:14:46,423 --> 00:14:50,889
And eventually, you develop a love which is non-attached.

186
00:14:50,909 --> 00:14:51,571
What does that mean?

187
00:14:51,610 --> 00:14:54,413
Does it mean that sometimes there's a detached love?

188
00:14:54,433 --> 00:14:57,817
It sounds cold, it sounds horrible, detached love, you know.

189
00:14:58,779 --> 00:15:01,984
But all it means is a love which is not dependent on the object.

190
00:15:03,745 --> 00:15:09,452
So it doesn't matter who stands before me, they get the same treatment.

191
00:15:09,472 --> 00:15:12,636
They get the same generosity, open-heartedness, etc.

192
00:15:14,058 --> 00:15:15,620
Now I'm not talking personally, understand me.

193
00:15:17,288 --> 00:15:35,448
but that's what we're trying to develop we're trying to develop that open hearted love not dependent on the object when it comes to compassion you can see the same thing the

194
00:15:37,318 --> 00:15:39,962
The obvious enemy of compassion, of course, is cruelty.

195
00:15:40,023 --> 00:15:41,144
It's completely the opposite.

196
00:15:41,785 --> 00:15:47,013
Compassion is a desire, this is how it's stated, is a desire to alleviate somebody's suffering.

197
00:15:47,072 --> 00:15:47,774
It's as simple as that.

198
00:15:48,455 --> 00:15:52,640
You want to help somebody who's in some sort of pain or suffering.

199
00:15:52,660 --> 00:15:53,562
Cruelty is the opposite.

200
00:15:53,582 --> 00:15:54,484
You want to enjoy it.

201
00:15:57,467 --> 00:16:05,039
The worst hell in Buddhism is reserved to those who are cruel, because it's obviously the complete opposite of the Buddhist teaching.

202
00:16:05,059 --> 00:16:12,711
I mean, here it is going around telling everybody how to alleviate suffering, and there are people going around purposely trying to make people suffer.

203
00:16:13,932 --> 00:16:17,197
In Buddhist understanding, there's nothing worse.

204
00:16:19,844 --> 00:16:34,500
So again, when we feel that cruelty, you know, that very subtle desire to put somebody down, slander them, stand on their toe when they're not looking, things like that, give them a push onto the...

205
00:16:34,520 --> 00:16:43,370
When you feel that, you know, when you don't like somebody and you hear that they've got a serious illness and you can hear yourself saying, good...

206
00:16:44,092 --> 00:16:47,811
There are all these little cruelties stuck inside us, you see.

207
00:16:48,273 --> 00:16:49,900
So he mustn't feel guilty about that.

208
00:16:49,921 --> 00:16:51,167
See, that's something else.

209
00:16:51,703 --> 00:16:54,967
We're not supposed to feel guilty about conditioning.

210
00:16:55,128 --> 00:17:00,714
Conditionings that we end up with are being manufactured, rather, out of ignorance, out of delusion.

211
00:17:00,774 --> 00:17:01,995
So now we're coming out of that.

212
00:17:02,336 --> 00:17:05,799
We're coming to a point of wisdom where we recognize, that wasn't very nice.

213
00:17:06,981 --> 00:17:08,242
One doesn't blame oneself.

214
00:17:08,343 --> 00:17:12,988
One just recognizes, that's a conditioning I don't want to develop.

215
00:17:13,008 --> 00:17:13,868
It's as simple as that.

216
00:17:13,888 --> 00:17:16,092
I just don't want to develop that conditioning anymore.

217
00:17:16,071 --> 00:17:19,598
So we know that conditioning will come up again and will fall again.

218
00:17:19,659 --> 00:17:23,748
But our attitude now is we don't want to develop it anymore.

219
00:17:23,788 --> 00:17:24,910
So we get more skillful.

220
00:17:25,029 --> 00:17:26,913
We don't feed it anymore.

221
00:17:28,718 --> 00:17:30,461
And eventually it dies away.

222
00:17:30,821 --> 00:17:33,928
Or at least it doesn't hijack us.

223
00:17:33,968 --> 00:17:34,890
That's what we don't want.

224
00:17:40,000 --> 00:17:48,423
Guilt and shame in Buddhism, the Buddha calls them the two guardians of society.

225
00:17:49,450 --> 00:17:54,914
But he's not referring here to the guilt we feel when we do something wrong, the dread of consequences.

226
00:17:55,415 --> 00:18:02,923
And he's not referring to the shame we feel when there's a gaffe, a social gaffe or something, or we hurt somebody.

227
00:18:03,103 --> 00:18:06,506
He's not talking about the consequence of unskillful action.

228
00:18:07,287 --> 00:18:17,836
He's talking about that little memory, that little warning that comes up when we are tempted to fiddle the taxes.

229
00:18:19,369 --> 00:18:34,323
which is highly topical, when we're tempted, as soon as the temptation comes, you see, the fear of consequence arises, just as a memory, the shame, you see, and immediately they guard us from doing that.

230
00:18:35,023 --> 00:18:39,607
If that's not internalized, that's not internalized, well, that's a psychopath, isn't it?

231
00:18:39,627 --> 00:18:43,490
A psychopath has no sense, a sociopath, they've no sense of right and wrong.

232
00:18:43,510 --> 00:18:47,875
You see these kids, you know, no sense of right and wrong.

233
00:18:50,503 --> 00:18:51,285
No sense of shame.

234
00:18:52,226 --> 00:19:01,936
There was that incredible thing I heard on the radio or television, I can't remember, where that little black boy was killed in London.

235
00:19:02,718 --> 00:19:05,180
Damilola Taylor, that's right.

236
00:19:05,200 --> 00:19:09,325
And they interviewed all the young people, the police interviewed.

237
00:19:09,345 --> 00:19:18,434
And one of the young kids, we're talking 10, 12 years old, so the policeman's asking this question, and he nuts him, broke his nose.

238
00:19:20,271 --> 00:19:23,517
It's amazing, isn't it?

239
00:19:23,538 --> 00:19:25,279
It wasn't within my generation to do that.

240
00:19:26,201 --> 00:19:28,826
There's just absolutely no fear of consequence.

241
00:19:28,846 --> 00:19:32,332
It can't be touched.

242
00:19:32,352 --> 00:19:33,815
And it just produces anarchy, doesn't it?

243
00:19:33,875 --> 00:19:35,057
It produces terrible stuff.

244
00:19:36,826 --> 00:19:46,634
So those two things, fear of consequence, I'm not talking about now the guilt which arises from a feeling of being evil.

245
00:19:46,934 --> 00:19:48,016
That's something else.

246
00:19:48,036 --> 00:19:49,958
That's a sort of existential guilt, you might say.

247
00:19:50,097 --> 00:19:53,040
That goes deeper in a definition of self.

248
00:19:54,121 --> 00:19:54,781
I am evil.

249
00:19:55,182 --> 00:20:01,307
So when that comes up, just note it and let it pass.

250
00:20:01,327 --> 00:20:04,790
No, I'm just talking about those feelings of dread, you know, like you didn't...

251
00:20:04,770 --> 00:20:08,056
You shouldn't have done that, something's going to happen at work, that sort of thing.

252
00:20:08,797 --> 00:20:10,660
And they become your guardians, see?

253
00:20:11,520 --> 00:20:12,962
So that's a sort of sensitivity.

254
00:20:16,868 --> 00:20:20,394
So cruelty is the opposite of compassion.

255
00:20:20,653 --> 00:20:23,377
The subtle enemy is grief.

256
00:20:25,340 --> 00:20:25,902
Grief.

257
00:20:27,281 --> 00:20:28,084
It's interesting, isn't it?

258
00:20:28,785 --> 00:20:30,769
Grief.

259
00:20:30,789 --> 00:20:31,932
Subtle enemy is grief.

260
00:20:32,814 --> 00:20:40,130
So often people grieve for somebody, pity, pity their state.

261
00:20:42,094 --> 00:20:42,635
So what's that?

262
00:20:42,675 --> 00:20:44,159
What's happening there when you do that?

263
00:20:45,883 --> 00:20:46,944
Where's that coming from?

264
00:20:49,287 --> 00:21:01,443
I mean, the desire, if somebody's sick or somebody, whatever, and you want to help them, the desire should be a joyful desire, a desire to help, a desire to help them in their situation, lend them some money, whatever.

265
00:21:03,185 --> 00:21:07,151
But if you slip into pity, pity them, what's happening there, you see?

266
00:21:09,253 --> 00:21:10,496
Can you agree with some of these thoughts?

267
00:21:11,998 --> 00:21:12,679
I mean, you haven't said anything.

268
00:21:13,267 --> 00:21:15,669
Well, the question is, is it necessary?

269
00:21:16,210 --> 00:21:18,251
I mean, we do it.

270
00:21:19,432 --> 00:21:21,536
We do it, but does it help?

271
00:21:21,715 --> 00:21:23,156
Does it help to pity somebody?

272
00:21:23,498 --> 00:21:25,759
I mean, how do we feel when somebody pities us?

273
00:21:26,980 --> 00:21:28,383
It's coming from a conceit, isn't it?

274
00:21:28,522 --> 00:21:37,451
It's coming from some place, almost, I always feel it's coming from some place of displaced fear, actually, and anxiety might happen to me.

275
00:21:39,962 --> 00:21:42,886
And it gets in the way, of course, because then you overdo.

276
00:21:42,926 --> 00:21:43,928
You overdo.

277
00:21:43,948 --> 00:21:45,369
You get into that do-gooder thing.

278
00:21:46,652 --> 00:21:47,752
Because you're compensating.

279
00:21:49,075 --> 00:21:49,734
Oh, let me help you.

280
00:21:49,755 --> 00:21:50,276
Let me help you.

281
00:21:50,296 --> 00:21:50,696
Go away.

282
00:21:54,582 --> 00:21:59,607
And the other subtle one of compassionate action is compassion.

283
00:22:00,212 --> 00:22:04,808
that when we do something out of compassion, when we help somebody, we do get a pleasant feeling.

284
00:22:05,811 --> 00:22:12,315
But when we make that pleasant feeling the purpose for doing, then of course we end up as a real do-gooder then.

285
00:22:13,679 --> 00:22:21,448
So I always think, supposing now you went along to your friend and said, you heard they were sick.

286
00:22:21,867 --> 00:22:23,430
So you said, you go along and help them.

287
00:22:23,470 --> 00:22:26,472
I'll come over and help you.

288
00:22:26,733 --> 00:22:29,896
So you go over there with this idea of cooking them chicken soup or something.

289
00:22:30,778 --> 00:22:36,884
When you get there, they say, can you clean the toilet?

290
00:22:37,455 --> 00:22:38,498
I didn't come here to do that.

291
00:22:42,384 --> 00:22:43,766
See what I mean?

292
00:22:43,886 --> 00:22:52,000
Whenever we're acting out of compassion and very subtly we're doing it in order to feel happy, we don't want to do what another person wants us to do.

293
00:22:52,441 --> 00:22:54,063
We want to do what I want to do for you.

294
00:22:54,124 --> 00:22:56,207
That's really oppressive.

295
00:22:58,211 --> 00:23:01,816
So again, you can't kill that conditioning.

296
00:23:01,855 --> 00:23:07,240
You've really got to accept that that's the way it is, that's the conditioning arising.

297
00:23:08,321 --> 00:23:12,527
And then, having acknowledged that, you may be doing it in order to feel happy.

298
00:23:12,846 --> 00:23:15,249
You see, you just acknowledge it, it's there within the heart.

299
00:23:16,210 --> 00:23:21,154
But there's also the true compassionate desire to alleviate somebody's suffering.

300
00:23:21,174 --> 00:23:23,798
So you make that your conscious desire.

301
00:23:24,132 --> 00:23:29,365
And the conscious desire that you empower is your new conditioning.

302
00:23:29,885 --> 00:23:37,365
So the more you empower a positive thought to help somebody in whatever way they want to be helped,

303
00:23:38,037 --> 00:23:42,461
See, that is developing the upper part of the egg, that's developing the compassion.

304
00:23:42,961 --> 00:23:49,689
It doesn't mean to say that there won't be all that disgust coming up, fancy asking me to clean the toilet, all that sort of stuff.

305
00:23:50,088 --> 00:23:55,134
So that still comes up, but it's a sort of afterthought, it's a leftover.

306
00:23:55,555 --> 00:23:58,938
One hasn't empowered that.

307
00:24:01,000 --> 00:24:02,761
So it's the same with generosity.

308
00:24:03,873 --> 00:24:16,548
When we give something, you know, a present or a donation or whatever, you see, as you give, there may be some feeling of goodness about it for the benefit of others.

309
00:24:17,209 --> 00:24:19,010
So you might be doing it for that reason.

310
00:24:19,771 --> 00:24:21,834
You might be doing it for guilt, I've got too much money.

311
00:24:23,496 --> 00:24:25,357
Not too many of those, but...

312
00:24:28,155 --> 00:24:39,315
But what you do is, before you give, before you actually commit the action, you have to suffuse your heart and mind with the right intention.

313
00:24:40,416 --> 00:24:42,720
So I'm giving this for the benefit of others.

314
00:24:43,442 --> 00:24:46,326
And when it's there, there's a real purposeful giving.

315
00:24:46,767 --> 00:24:47,689
That's when you give.

316
00:24:47,929 --> 00:24:52,576
As soon as you act, that's your karma, that's your action, that's your conditioning.

317
00:24:53,519 --> 00:25:05,855
So there's an intention, there's an action, and those actions produce a conditioning, which grow depending on how you keep on supporting that intention.

318
00:25:07,116 --> 00:25:11,583
So there you are, and you've given, and you've said, you know, I give for the benefit of others.

319
00:25:11,722 --> 00:25:13,546
Really suffuse that and you give it, you see.

320
00:25:13,566 --> 00:25:14,787
And you hear this little voice, you see.

321
00:25:15,749 --> 00:25:17,451
You are so wonderful.

322
00:25:17,734 --> 00:25:21,721
Now you see, that's old conditioning.

323
00:25:21,740 --> 00:25:27,349
That's coming up from the old thing about wanting to be somebody's pet, wanting to be somebody's friend.

324
00:25:28,811 --> 00:25:30,054
So you just recognize that.

325
00:25:30,074 --> 00:25:32,096
That's the old conditioning.

326
00:25:32,116 --> 00:25:33,077
You haven't empowered that.

327
00:25:34,780 --> 00:25:36,083
And eventually that would die away.

328
00:25:37,244 --> 00:25:38,926
Or you might get the other side, you know.

329
00:25:39,268 --> 00:25:40,890
Too much, get some back.

330
00:25:41,630 --> 00:25:45,035
So you just let it go, pass away.

331
00:25:45,055 --> 00:25:48,599
If you feel guilty about that, you know the guilt, because it's inappropriate.

332
00:25:49,260 --> 00:25:54,067
He didn't mean, that wasn't what was empowered, that's just an old conditioning coming through.

333
00:25:58,252 --> 00:26:02,979
So again, you can see the purpose of mindfulness.

334
00:26:03,559 --> 00:26:04,361
You don't just give.

335
00:26:05,102 --> 00:26:07,806
So you have to stop for a minute and really get your heart right.

336
00:26:09,051 --> 00:26:10,252
You don't just go out and do good.

337
00:26:10,272 --> 00:26:11,535
You really get your heart right.

338
00:26:12,115 --> 00:26:13,356
When somebody says, can you help me?

339
00:26:13,557 --> 00:26:14,238
You don't say yes.

340
00:26:15,740 --> 00:26:17,040
A lot of us suffer from that, don't we?

341
00:26:17,221 --> 00:26:17,721
I mean, I do.

342
00:26:18,143 --> 00:26:18,722
Can you do yes?

343
00:26:19,084 --> 00:26:22,367
And then you think, I don't want to do that.

344
00:26:22,387 --> 00:26:23,588
If you just stop a minute, you see.

345
00:26:23,848 --> 00:26:25,431
There's all these little tricks of language.

346
00:26:25,932 --> 00:26:26,792
Well, I might be busy.

347
00:26:26,813 --> 00:26:28,273
I'll have to look that up in my diary.

348
00:26:28,454 --> 00:26:34,902
And then so long as you've got the good reason for doing it, then you do it.

349
00:26:34,981 --> 00:26:37,404
If you don't want to do it, you shouldn't feel guilty about that.

350
00:26:39,038 --> 00:26:42,721
If you feel guilty about that, then one should note that, one should see, ah, guilt.

351
00:26:44,262 --> 00:26:45,864
Feel it, allow it to pass away.

352
00:26:48,967 --> 00:27:07,324
So you can see that this, what we're doing here as a sitting practice, is specifically important every day, every moment of our lives, to keep that awareness going, so that when you're talking to somebody, there is that more spacious awareness, that you're aware of what they're saying, but you're also aware of your reaction here.

353
00:27:08,603 --> 00:27:10,644
Not to always be going outward.

354
00:27:12,165 --> 00:27:13,528
Sort of balanced awareness.

355
00:27:14,788 --> 00:27:16,651
Even now as you're listening to me you can be aware.

356
00:27:22,756 --> 00:27:23,257
Joy.

357
00:27:30,423 --> 00:27:33,686
The enemy of joy is jealousy.

358
00:27:34,548 --> 00:27:34,948
Envy.

359
00:27:37,087 --> 00:27:38,589
It really cuts through, doesn't it?

360
00:27:38,710 --> 00:27:42,435
You can't feel joyful for somebody if you're jealous of them.

361
00:27:46,682 --> 00:27:57,538
So when jealousy comes up, and it's one of those things that we never, we don't like to acknowledge about ourselves at all, the fact that we're envious or jealous, because what it's suggesting is that somebody's better than us.

362
00:27:58,720 --> 00:28:00,221
Nobody wants to believe that.

363
00:28:01,924 --> 00:28:06,791
And I just make an arbitrary distinction between envy and jealousy all over it.

364
00:28:07,243 --> 00:28:08,826
Maybe it's not quite like that.

365
00:28:09,146 --> 00:28:16,277
But envy is wanting what they have and jealousy is wanting what they have and hating them for having it.

366
00:28:18,059 --> 00:28:23,346
Which is an added twist.

367
00:28:23,366 --> 00:28:29,296
So again, all you can do is accept that that's there and let it burn, pass away.

368
00:28:29,936 --> 00:28:35,664
And of course the joy that comes up is then that much more joyful.

369
00:28:37,500 --> 00:28:40,365
You can feel great joy, can't you, for people whom you love.

370
00:28:40,726 --> 00:28:44,752
That's not a problem.

371
00:28:44,772 --> 00:28:46,655
Parent for their children, it comes naturally.

372
00:28:46,876 --> 00:28:49,141
Sympathetic joy, reciprocal joy.

373
00:28:57,894 --> 00:29:01,642
And the subtle thing is again that sort of attachment.

374
00:29:01,842 --> 00:29:03,744
Wanting to be joyful...

375
00:29:04,028 --> 00:29:06,912
in order to feel always joyful.

376
00:29:07,553 --> 00:29:13,059
So you're not joyful for somebody, you're only joyful for them because it makes you joyful.

377
00:29:14,301 --> 00:29:19,709
So again, you're turning that person into an object and you want them to do things that are joyful for you.

378
00:29:19,729 --> 00:29:23,994
So again, you make people do things that make you happy.

379
00:29:24,987 --> 00:29:29,031
I mean, that's also a parental thing sometimes, isn't it?

380
00:29:29,633 --> 00:29:37,782
The parent wants the child to be in a way that they foresee would be good for the child, which would make them feel happy about their child, you know?

381
00:29:38,825 --> 00:29:40,326
Getting a degree and stuff like that.

382
00:29:41,327 --> 00:29:42,809
Pushing them.

383
00:29:42,829 --> 00:29:44,551
And it's done under the guise of it's good for you.

384
00:29:44,612 --> 00:29:50,138
But often it's this business of, you know, I want to feel happy about you.

385
00:29:51,221 --> 00:29:53,002
But that's not a sympathetic joy.

386
00:29:54,451 --> 00:29:55,613
Not reciprocal joy.

387
00:29:59,178 --> 00:30:01,642
And that's something you can develop, you know.

388
00:30:01,982 --> 00:30:08,873
You can develop joy every time you hear of somebody who has won the lottery and stuff like that.

389
00:30:09,815 --> 00:30:10,936
To say to yourself, how wonderful.

390
00:30:11,436 --> 00:30:12,219
May they be happy.

391
00:30:14,521 --> 00:30:18,888
The person who got the job that you wanted, may they be happy.

392
00:30:23,392 --> 00:30:26,194
And then finally there's equanimity.

393
00:30:27,516 --> 00:30:29,198
So now equanimity is a funny one.

394
00:30:29,258 --> 00:30:31,520
It's a funny word, equanimity.

395
00:30:31,941 --> 00:30:34,044
It's balance of mind.

396
00:30:34,544 --> 00:30:35,684
A balance of mind.

397
00:30:36,145 --> 00:30:38,428
So you expect a judge to be equanimous.

398
00:30:38,607 --> 00:30:43,232
No matter what the emotional state is in the court, you expect them to be above it.

399
00:30:43,252 --> 00:30:46,757
You expect them not to get caught up in that.

400
00:30:46,777 --> 00:30:47,897
Not to be judgmental.

401
00:30:49,800 --> 00:30:53,044
So obviously there's your main enemy.

402
00:30:53,429 --> 00:30:57,453
be judgmental, to lose that balance of mind, to take sides.

403
00:30:59,957 --> 00:31:00,596
You lose it.

404
00:31:01,878 --> 00:31:10,848
And the subtle enemy is just again seeking to be calm for calm's sake.

405
00:31:11,349 --> 00:31:17,596
See, as soon as you make these virtues their purpose, it immediately corrupts it.

406
00:31:18,826 --> 00:31:30,576
If you want to be generous to get the joy of generosity, then it corrupts your generosity, because often you're asked to be generous with exactly that which you don't want to give.

407
00:31:32,018 --> 00:31:36,942
Some people are very generous with their time, others with their money, some with neither.

408
00:31:37,843 --> 00:31:39,585
It's just a fact.

409
00:31:40,265 --> 00:31:46,790
So some people might be very generous with their time, but if you ask them for a penny for a cup of tea, they don't want to see you.

410
00:31:47,597 --> 00:31:51,883
And that's them, that's them, drawing a circle around their idea of generosity.

411
00:31:53,825 --> 00:32:05,377
So as soon as you start practicing a virtue for the virtue's sake, then you'll find yourself in this, you'll find yourself drawing a line, you'll find yourself being unable to develop it illimitably.

412
00:32:06,480 --> 00:32:07,140
Illimitably.

413
00:32:10,163 --> 00:32:13,807
So that, these are the four principles.

414
00:32:14,057 --> 00:32:14,878
Illimitables.

415
00:32:15,960 --> 00:32:24,809
And you can see that their development is equally important to developing this vipassana, this insight.

416
00:32:24,829 --> 00:32:28,934
Yeah?

417
00:32:28,954 --> 00:32:30,056
Any questions about that?

418
00:32:30,076 --> 00:32:31,237
Anything that's come up about that?

419
00:32:33,519 --> 00:32:34,401
Clarifications?

420
00:32:34,961 --> 00:32:35,701
Observations?

421
00:32:37,003 --> 00:32:37,664
Criticism?

422
00:32:38,925 --> 00:32:40,587
What did you say earlier in the interview?

423
00:32:42,037 --> 00:32:44,567
Doing it for itself.

424
00:32:45,250 --> 00:32:47,700
Yeah, always making it its own object.

425
00:32:48,261 --> 00:32:50,190
To be joyful in order to be joyful.

426
00:32:51,587 --> 00:33:00,759
It took me a second when you were referring back, when you were saying about, you know, guys are in the basement.

427
00:33:00,778 --> 00:33:02,540
It took me two seconds to say, who's putting up on you?

428
00:33:06,846 --> 00:33:08,107
In this case, it was the kid.

429
00:33:08,748 --> 00:33:20,261
But in relation to the last one, eponymity, which you were saying there, and you've made an earlier reference to kids, or these young people, you know, and...

430
00:33:22,739 --> 00:33:32,664
It sort of came across to me that it was a sort of general criticism.

431
00:33:34,837 --> 00:33:39,384
of people who would be in a certain condition and would only know how to react one way.

432
00:33:40,247 --> 00:33:43,471
Oh, yeah.

433
00:33:43,711 --> 00:33:45,816
Oh, no, that's presumed.

434
00:33:46,457 --> 00:33:47,377
They've not been taught.

435
00:33:47,417 --> 00:33:49,602
They're in a sort of vicious circle.

436
00:33:50,703 --> 00:33:56,012
Family and social circumstance, definitely.

437
00:33:56,032 --> 00:34:00,019
But they, you see, these children, if they move into the spiritual life,

438
00:34:00,775 --> 00:34:01,597
They can't blame.

439
00:34:01,659 --> 00:34:05,915
They can't put blame on that social circumstance and parents and all that.

440
00:34:07,101 --> 00:34:08,726
So this is the point.

441
00:34:08,807 --> 00:34:22,585
If you keep doing that, then you're unable to come out of the vicious circle within yourself, because you presume that this conditioning has been caused by others, whereas what we've discovered is that it's actually produced by ourselves.

442
00:34:23,586 --> 00:34:30,735
Now, you've got to make a distinction between responsibility and culpability.

443
00:34:31,577 --> 00:34:36,802
You're not to be blamed because we've ended up with cruelty in our hearts, but we are responsible for it.

444
00:34:37,224 --> 00:34:38,324
That's a subtle difference.

445
00:34:39,621 --> 00:34:47,829
In other words, unwittingly, at an early age, because of circumstances, I have created within myself a lot of cruelty.

446
00:34:50,172 --> 00:34:57,840
Now, I can't be blamed for that because at that time I was unaware, deluded.

447
00:34:58,561 --> 00:35:04,746
Now I end up, through the meditation, all through ordinary life, realizing how much cruelty is in my system.

448
00:35:06,568 --> 00:35:08,751
So it's my responsibility now to get rid of it.

449
00:35:09,793 --> 00:35:13,239
See?

450
00:35:13,260 --> 00:35:15,503
That's a relief, isn't it, when we think like that?

451
00:35:17,588 --> 00:35:21,594
We're not looking to blame anybody or to put the finger on somebody.

452
00:35:22,036 --> 00:35:26,523
All we've done is that we've ended up with this personality, with this conditioning.

453
00:35:26,543 --> 00:35:29,809
And now that we've woken up to it, the job is to clear it out.

454
00:35:30,150 --> 00:35:31,853
And here's a system that can help.

455
00:35:34,010 --> 00:35:40,414
If we start blaming or looking for somebody to blame, then that creates another negativity in the heart, doesn't it?

456
00:35:40,536 --> 00:35:41,639
Revenge and all that.

457
00:35:46,851 --> 00:35:48,193
Yes, sure.

458
00:35:48,914 --> 00:36:04,193
So it is in the nature of the being then that we have a constant battle, even if we go to a certain level of cruelty and compassion and try and keep on moving forward.

459
00:36:06,175 --> 00:36:09,420
Is it a part of being human?

460
00:36:09,440 --> 00:36:14,766
Well, you see, at some point in existence,

461
00:36:14,847 --> 00:36:20,253
As consciousness grows, we simply make this mistake of thinking that this is what we are.

462
00:36:21,835 --> 00:36:22,755
That's the big problem.

463
00:36:23,335 --> 00:36:30,423
So therefore, you get into this contradiction with the world.

464
00:36:30,523 --> 00:36:39,193
The contradiction is, this is me, and I want to be happy, so I'll accumulate around me things that make me happy.

465
00:36:40,594 --> 00:36:44,179
And that moves to greed, it moves to crime, etc., etc., yeah?

466
00:36:44,563 --> 00:36:49,630
Anything that touches me, which makes me feel unhappy, then I want to push away.

467
00:36:50,210 --> 00:36:54,054
So it moves to hatred, cruelty, all that sort of stuff.

468
00:36:54,074 --> 00:36:56,418
So I'm caught in that contradiction all the time.

469
00:36:56,577 --> 00:36:58,641
I'm always in a state of contradiction.

470
00:37:00,443 --> 00:37:06,150
And the only way I can overcome that is by seeing that contradiction and stop playing that game.

471
00:37:06,652 --> 00:37:08,996
So the image I have is of a triangle.

472
00:37:09,617 --> 00:37:14,284
So the bottom part of the triangle is this aversion, accumulation, aversion, greed.

473
00:37:14,925 --> 00:37:18,632
And we're constantly running up and down this base of a triangle, completely caught up in it.

474
00:37:19,713 --> 00:37:24,039
When we lift ourselves up out of that in meditation, we're at the apex of a triangle.

475
00:37:24,061 --> 00:37:25,041
We can see this gain.

476
00:37:25,782 --> 00:37:34,516
So that's why I say in that exercise on forgiving somebody, you bring up the memory and you can see how you want to get your own back.

477
00:37:34,547 --> 00:37:36,713
You don't want to forgive them.

478
00:37:36,833 --> 00:37:37,976
You can see that.

479
00:37:37,996 --> 00:37:39,739
And that's the game of the base of the triangle.

480
00:37:40,422 --> 00:37:46,496
When you stand up at the top and you just watch this game, because you're not in it, you're not empowering it.

481
00:37:47,237 --> 00:37:48,320
So it has to die away.

482
00:37:48,360 --> 00:37:51,847
And that's the role of will in Buddhism.

483
00:37:52,452 --> 00:37:54,615
The will is what empowers the gain.

484
00:37:55,016 --> 00:38:02,451
So as soon as you withdraw your attention from it, withdraw your awareness from that level, that's a level of self.

485
00:38:03,032 --> 00:38:08,824
And you come to the level of observing that, then of course you've withdrawn the energy from it.

486
00:38:10,407 --> 00:38:13,211
So it goes on and on, but eventually it dies away.

487
00:38:20,228 --> 00:38:26,778
But that's a very important distinction to make between responsibility and blame, and blaming somebody.

488
00:38:29,143 --> 00:38:36,536
And remember that in Buddhist understanding, nobody eventually escapes their problems.

489
00:38:37,077 --> 00:38:42,465
So if somebody's being cruel, they themselves will suffer the consequence of that.

490
00:38:42,485 --> 00:38:46,152
So the idea of punishment is untenable in Buddhism.

491
00:38:48,847 --> 00:38:54,233
That doesn't mean to say you can't put somebody away if they're a danger or put them somewhere they can be re-educated or something.

492
00:38:54,655 --> 00:38:57,418
But you can't have the attitude of punishing them.

493
00:38:57,557 --> 00:38:59,280
It's a form of revenge.

494
00:39:02,884 --> 00:39:06,728
Which doesn't mean to say that in Buddhist countries people don't punish each other.

495
00:39:09,210 --> 00:39:10,693
But it's untenable.

496
00:39:11,072 --> 00:39:12,233
Because it's just understood.

497
00:39:12,313 --> 00:39:16,458
As soon as somebody does harm, they will suffer the consequence of that.

498
00:39:16,793 --> 00:39:17,673
And that's what we're doing.

499
00:39:17,713 --> 00:39:20,657
Every time you sit, I mean, all that restlessness and all that stuff, what is it?

500
00:39:20,998 --> 00:39:21,679
Where's that coming from?

501
00:39:22,521 --> 00:39:29,610
Some of it's coming from deluded decisions at a time when we weren't aware.

502
00:39:30,110 --> 00:39:33,396
But some of them are coming from, you know, active wrongdoing.

503
00:39:43,369 --> 00:39:43,469
Yeah?

504
00:39:43,489 --> 00:39:45,972
When is it appropriate to intervene in a situation which is really not in your business, even though it's obviously obvious?

505
00:39:46,342 --> 00:40:09,007
Yeah, there was...

506
00:40:09,443 --> 00:40:16,657
This comes up, you know, I had with a friend of mine out in Thailand and he had this idea of detachment.

507
00:40:16,699 --> 00:40:18,242
He was developing detachment.

508
00:40:19,804 --> 00:40:22,731
So when he saw a cat playing around with a mouse, he didn't do anything.

509
00:40:22,751 --> 00:40:24,414
He was completely detached.

510
00:40:26,572 --> 00:40:34,563
Whereas I've seen also in monasteries where a cat has got hold of a bird, the monk has run out and, you know, given the cat a kick.

511
00:40:37,746 --> 00:40:38,789
And then just held the bird up.

512
00:40:38,809 --> 00:40:39,929
It was actually quite beautiful.

513
00:40:39,969 --> 00:40:41,532
The bird had been killed.

514
00:40:41,572 --> 00:40:43,574
Its lungs had been punctured.

515
00:40:43,594 --> 00:40:45,217
And he just held it up, you know, with its wings.

516
00:40:45,577 --> 00:40:49,422
All compounded things arise and pass away.

517
00:40:52,255 --> 00:41:00,844
I should think those sort of decisions really, it's up to a person's own sensitivity to that, whether they're open to advice.

518
00:41:00,864 --> 00:41:05,909
Sometimes you give advice or you want to help, but actually you're making things worse because they don't want to know.

519
00:41:05,969 --> 00:41:12,916
But our attitude should be, of course, yes, to undermine suffering wherever we see it.

520
00:41:14,237 --> 00:41:19,983
I mean, this is what's come up with all this business of, you know, these wars on terrorists and stuff, you know.

521
00:41:22,293 --> 00:41:25,135
the massacre in Rwanda, for instance.

522
00:41:26,577 --> 00:41:30,983
If we'd have been a more advanced international society, we probably wouldn't have let that happen.

523
00:41:33,125 --> 00:41:34,706
Just got in there and pulled them apart.

524
00:41:43,175 --> 00:41:45,177
Yeah, sometimes it's wise not to say anything, huh?

525
00:41:48,652 --> 00:41:50,496
Time, place and suitability.

526
00:41:50,876 --> 00:41:52,139
Right speech, the Buddha says.

527
00:41:52,199 --> 00:41:56,690
When you want to say something, make sure it's suitable.

528
00:41:56,710 --> 00:42:00,400
Make sure it's the right time and the right place.
